english:
  title: A Farewell Dedication for Master Lo Returning Westward
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Son of Heaven favored our Eastern Kingdom as the first to receive the teachings of civilization. Thus, generation after generation, he granted us the privilege of maintaining our own court and delegated to us the administration of royal affairs. Yet the officials in our service are all appointed by our own selection, not chosen by the imperial court itself. In such circumstances, how could scholars from the Central Plain ever come to us? And those of refined spirit, content in their gardens and refusing to serve—how could we ever bind them to our soil?

    Those who do take office here are mostly men eager to sell their talents. At first, they wag their tails in fear of being rejected; in the end, once satisfied, they fly away like hawks, even coming to despise their patrons. This is commonplace. Thus, when Eastern men receive guests, though their faces show respect, their hearts do not necessarily align. This is the nature of our land.

    Now comes Master Lo Baekgyeong of Daening, who has arrived as an Academy Official in the capital. I, being afflicted, had withdrawn from public life and seldom mingled even with villagers. When Master Lo arrived, I heard of it only after considerable time had passed. I wished to visit him and pay my respects, but instead, Master Lo graciously sought me out first. I received him with surprise and spoke with him at length. His words were measured and gentle, his countenance serene, his heart at ease—truly a man of integrity who bears responsibility without pretension.

    After this, we visited each other often. Learning of his family, I found he is the son of the esteemed Darjae, the present Circuit Inspector of Shenyang, and the grandson of the late Dongam, the former Superintendent of the廉訪 of Hedong and Shanxi. I had heard that Lo Dongam was revered as a master by Northern scholars, and that Master Lo had served under this great teacher, thus his learning comes from an authentic lineage.

    I had long lamented that scholarly standards in the East had grown lax and neglected. With Master Lo's arrival, I thought surely he would inspire and revitalize us. But alas, it was not long before he was promoted and his term ended, and he took his leave. His students, left behind, lost their direction and made no further progress on the Way. Nor was it only his students who suffered so—Master Lo himself was here less than a year, and his influence bore little visible fruit. Can we truly expect that all Easterners would recognize Master Lo as a true teacher of our tradition?

    And yet, moving forward is difficult while retreating is easy—such is the mark of the wise man's discernment. That Master Lo has conducted himself with such wisdom reflects well upon him, bringing him neither loss nor gain in my eyes. What grieves me is only this: that no one had the means to comfort him enough to make him wish to stay, as one might comfort Zisi. Since we cannot keep him, I cannot remain silent in our fellowship of learning. I have therefore invited those who know him to each compose a poem in his honor. But fearing that some may not truly know Master Lo and might treat him merely as an ordinary visitor, I have first explained how such men of superficial talent comport themselves, so that all may understand: Master Lo is no such creature. He is a true scholar of our tradition, a man of distinguished family—of an entirely different order altogether.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zisi (子思) was the grandson of Confucius, renowned for his steadfast commitment to learning and virtue. The reference suggests a parallel to Master Lo's dedication to the Way despite circumstances.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Eastern Kingdom' (東國) refers to Korea, which received Chinese civilization and maintained semi-autonomous scholarly and administrative traditions.
  - key: ''
    value: Dongam (東庵), Master Lo's grandfather, was a famous Northern Chinese Confucian scholar and official, establishing the pedigree and authenticity of Master Lo's learning.
